VALUES
(44, 9, 28, 44, 1, 21, 21, NULL, 'In and Out Among Us', 'This connection highlights the shared phrase ''going in and out,'' which emphasizes the continuous presence and fellowship of the apostles with Jesus and later with Paul. Both passages emphasize the importance of companionship in the early Christian community.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 28, 4, 27, 16, 17, 'coming in and going out', 'Leadership and Guidance in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a leader who guides the people, as seen in the phrase ''coming in and going out'' in Acts, which parallels the call for a leader to ''go out before them, and...bring them in'' in Numbers. This connection highlights the importance of shepherd-like leadership in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 28, 10, 5, 2, 2, 'coming in and going out', 'Leadership and Guidance in Israel', 'Both passages emphasize the role of leadership in guiding Israel. In Acts, the phrase ''coming in and going out'' suggests active participation in the community, similar to the leadership described in 2 Samuel where one is called to ''lead out and bring in Israel.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 28, 11, 3, 7, 7, 'coming in and going out', 'Connection of Leadership and Guidance', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of guidance in leadership. In Acts, the phrase ''coming in and going out'' suggests active participation and leadership, while in 1 Kings, the request for understanding how to ''go out or come in'' reflects a need for divine guidance in leadership roles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 28, 19, 121, 8, 8, 'coming in and going out', 'Preservation in Movement', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of ''going out and coming in,'' suggesting a divine protection over one''s movements. Acts 9:28 describes the physical presence of the believers in Jerusalem, while Psalms 121:8 speaks to God''s preservation in those movements.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 28, 43, 10, 9, 9, NULL, 'In and Out Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''going in and out,'' suggesting a movement that leads to safety and sustenance. This connection highlights the idea of community and belonging in the context of faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 28, 48, 1, 18, 18, 'coming in and going out at Jerusalem', 'Connection of Peter''s Presence', 'This connection highlights the presence of Peter in Jerusalem. Both passages emphasize the interactions of Paul with Peter during his time in the city.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 29, 44, 6, 1, 1, 'Grecians', 'Conflict with the Grecians', 'Both passages emphasize conflict involving the Grecians. In Acts 6:1, the Grecians express discontent, while in Acts 9:29, they seek to harm a bold speaker among them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 29, 44, 11, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Preaching to Grecians', 'Both passages emphasize the engagement with the Grecians. In Acts 9:29, the bold speaking against the Grecians precedes the later preaching to them in Acts 11:20.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 29, 47, 11, 26, 26, NULL, 'Perils Faced by Paul', 'This connection highlights the dangers Paul faced in his ministry. Both passages emphasize the threats from adversaries, whether from Grecians or false brethren.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 29, 65, 1, 9, 9, 'disputed', 'Disputing and Contending Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of disputing or contending. In Acts, the boldness in disputing reflects a confrontation, while Jude highlights a dispute involving Michael and the devil, showcasing a spiritual contention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 29, 65, 1, 3, 3, 'spake boldly in the name of the Lord Jesus', 'Contending for the Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the need to boldly defend one''s beliefs. Acts 9:29 illustrates Paul disputing against opposition, while Jude 1:3 encourages believers to earnestly contend for their faith.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 30, 44, 8, 40, 40, 'Cesarea', 'Connection between Cesarea and Tarsus', 'Both passages emphasize Cesarea as a significant location. In Acts 9:30, the brethren send Paul to Tarsus after he is in Cesarea, while in Acts 8:40, Philip preaches in Cesarea, highlighting its role in early Christian missions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 30, 44, 9, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Saul''s Origin', 'Both passages emphasize Saul''s identity as being from Tarsus. Acts 9:30 mentions his being sent to Tarsus, while Acts 9:11 identifies him as ''one called Saul, of Tarsus.''', 'keyword', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 30, 48, 1, 21, 21, 'sent him forth to Tarsus', 'Paul''s Journey to Tarsus', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement after being sent away. Both passages emphasize his transition into regions beyond Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 30, 40, 10, 23, 23, NULL, 'Persecution and Fleeing', 'This connection highlights the theme of fleeing due to persecution. In Acts 9:30, the brethren help Paul escape to Tarsus, paralleling Matthew 10:23''s instruction to flee to another city when persecuted.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 30, 40, 16, 13, 13, 'Cesarea', 'Connection Between Cesarea References', 'Both passages emphasize Cesarea as a significant location. In Acts, it serves as a point of departure for Paul, while in Matthew, it is a place of revelation about Jesus'' identity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 19, 111, 10, 10, 'walking in the fear of the Lord', 'Connection of Fear of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''the fear of the Lord'' as foundational to spiritual growth and wisdom. Acts 9:31 illustrates the churches being edified and multiplied through this fear, while Psalms 111:10 states it is the beginning of wisdom.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 43, 14, 16, 18, 'comfort of the Holy Ghost', 'Comfort of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Spirit as a source of comfort and support for believers. In Acts, the churches experience comfort from the Holy Ghost, while in John, Jesus promises the Comforter will abide with them forever.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 23, 33, 6, 6, 'the fear of the Lord', 'Connection of Fear of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''the fear of the Lord'' as a source of strength and stability. Acts highlights the churches'' growth through this reverence, while Isaiah presents it as a treasure that contributes to salvation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 20, 14, 26, 27, 'walking in the fear of the Lord', 'Connection of Fear and Confidence', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''the fear of the Lord'' as a source of strength and growth. Acts highlights the churches being edified and multiplied through this fear, while Proverbs connects it to strong confidence and life.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 20, 23, 17, 17, 'the fear of the Lord', 'Connection of Fear of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''the fear of the Lord'' as a guiding principle for believers. Acts 9:31 shows the churches growing while walking in this fear, paralleling Proverbs 23:17''s exhortation to maintain it throughout the day.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 16, 5, 9, 9, 'walking in the fear of the Lord', 'Fear of God and Multiplication', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of walking in the fear of God. Acts highlights the growth of the churches through this reverence, while Nehemiah calls for it to avoid reproach from enemies.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 31, 19, 86, 11, 11, 'walking in the fear of the Lord', 'Walking in Fear of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize walking in the fear of the Lord. Acts 9:31 mentions ''walking in the fear of the Lord,'' while Psalms 86:11 speaks of fearing God''s name. This connection highlights a shared theme of reverence and obedience.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 44, 9, 13, 13, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''saints.'' In Acts 9:13, Ananias refers to the saints in Jerusalem, while in Acts 9:32, Peter visits the saints in Lydda. This connection highlights the shared community of believers facing persecution.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 20, 2, 8, 8, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints and Preservation', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''saints.'' Acts 9:32 mentions Peter visiting the saints, while Proverbs 2:8 speaks of God preserving the way of His saints. This connection highlights the care and attention given to the faithful.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 44, 8, 25, 25, NULL, 'Peter''s Ministry and Evangelism', 'Both passages emphasize the active ministry of the apostles. In Acts 9:32, Peter is seen preaching to the saints, while in Acts 8:25, the apostles are preaching the gospel in various villages.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 19, 16, 3, 3, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''saints.'' Acts 9:32 refers to the saints in Lydda, while Psalms 16:3 speaks of the saints in the earth, highlighting their significance and the delight found in them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 40, 27, 52, 52, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''saints'' and their significance. In Acts, Peter visits the saints in Lydda, while in Matthew, the bodies of saints arise, indicating a connection in the portrayal of the faithful.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 45, 1, 7, 7, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''saints'' in both passages. Acts 9:32 refers to the ''saints'' in Lydda, while Romans 1:7 addresses those in Rome as ''called to be saints.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 32, 48, 2, 7, 9, 'the saints which dwelt at Lydda', 'Connection of Apostolic Missions', 'This connection highlights Peter''s role in the early church as he interacts with the saints, paralleling his mission to the circumcised with Paul''s mission to the uncircumcised. Both passages emphasize the distinct yet complementary roles of Peter and Paul in spreading the gospel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 42, 13, 16, 16, 'sick of the palsy', 'Healing and Bondage Connection', 'Both passages emphasize healing from physical ailments and the concept of being bound by illness. Eneas is described as being sick for eight years, while the woman in Luke is bound for eighteen years, highlighting the severity and duration of their conditions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 41, 2, 3, 11, 'sick of the palsy', 'Healing of the Paralytic', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of a man sick of the palsy. In Acts, Eneas is healed after eight years, while in Mark, a paralytic is healed by Jesus, showcasing the theme of miraculous healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 41, 5, 25, 25, NULL, 'Healing of Long-Term Illnesses', 'Both passages emphasize individuals suffering from long-term ailments, with Eneas being sick for eight years and the woman having an issue of blood for twelve years. This connection highlights the theme of prolonged suffering and the need for healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 43, 5, 5, 5, 'sick of the palsy', 'Connection of Healing Narratives', 'Both passages emphasize a man with a long-term infirmity. Eneas had been sick for eight years, while the man in John had an infirmity for thirty-eight years, highlighting the theme of prolonged suffering before healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 43, 9, 1, 1, NULL, 'Healing of the Disabled', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of individuals with significant disabilities. Eneas is described as being sick of the palsy, while the man in John was blind from birth, highlighting the theme of miraculous healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 44, 3, 2, 2, 'sick of the palsy', 'Healing of the Lame', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of individuals who are unable to walk due to physical ailments. Eneas is described as being sick of the palsy, while the man in Acts 3 is lame from birth, highlighting a theme of miraculous healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 33, 44, 4, 22, 22, NULL, 'Healing of the Sick', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing in both passages. Acts 9:33 mentions a man sick for eight years, while Acts 4:22 refers to a man healed who was above forty years old, emphasizing the transformative power of healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 34, 40, 9, 6, 6, 'arise, and make thy bed', 'Healing and Command to Arise', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''arise'' and the act of healing. In each instance, the healing is directly linked to the authority of Jesus Christ or the Son of Man.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 34, 44, 3, 6, 6, 'Jesus Christ maketh thee whole', 'Healing in Jesus'' Name', 'Both passages emphasize healing performed by Peter in the name of Jesus Christ. They illustrate the power of Jesus to restore physical health, as seen in the commands to ''arise'' and ''walk.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 34, 44, 3, 12, 12, 'Jesus Christ maketh thee whole', 'Healing Through Peter''s Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing performed by Peter, attributing the power to Jesus Christ. This connection highlights the role of faith and divine authority in the acts of healing.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 34, 40, 8, 3, 3, 'arose immediately', 'Healing by Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize immediate healing through the authority of Jesus. In Acts, Peter invokes Jesus'' name to heal Eneas, while in Matthew, Jesus directly commands healing, showcasing His power over illness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 34, 43, 2, 11, 11, 'Jesus Christ maketh thee whole', 'Healing and Belief in Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and the manifestation of Jesus'' power. In both passages, the act of healing leads to a response of belief in Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 44, 11, 21, 21, 'turned to the Lord', 'Turning to the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the response of people turning to the Lord after witnessing divine acts. This connection highlights the transformative impact of faith in the early church.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 13, 5, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Locations and Community', 'Both passages emphasize communities in specific regions, with Acts mentioning Lydda and Saron, while Chronicles refers to Sharon. This connection highlights the geographical significance of these areas in the biblical narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 44, 9, 42, 42, 'turned to the Lord', 'Belief in the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the response of people turning to faith in the Lord. The first mentions those in Lydda and Saron turning to the Lord, while the second notes that many in Joppa believed in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 23, 35, 2, 2, 'turned to the Lord', 'Transformation and Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation and glory. In Acts, the people turn to the Lord, reflecting the joy and glory mentioned in Isaiah, where the land rejoices and sees the glory of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 13, 27, 29, 29, NULL, 'Connection Between Lydda and Sharon', 'Both passages emphasize the region of Sharon, linking the healing in Lydda to a broader context of community and pastoral care. The mention of Sharon in both verses highlights its significance in the biblical narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 19, 22, 27, 27, 'turned to the Lord', 'Turning to the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of people turning to the Lord in both passages. Acts 9:35 describes individuals turning to the Lord after witnessing a miracle, while Psalms 22:27 speaks of all nations remembering and turning to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 35, 47, 3, 16, 16, 'turned to the Lord', 'Turning to the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of turning to the Lord in both passages. Acts 9:35 describes people turning to the Lord after witnessing a miracle, while 2 Corinthians 3:16 speaks of a similar turning that leads to the removal of a veil.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 56, 2, 7, 7, 'good works and almsdeeds which she did', 'Good Works and Almsdeeds', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on good works in both passages. Tabitha is described as ''full of good works and almsdeeds,'' while Titus encourages showing ''a pattern of good works.''', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 56, 3, 8, 8, 'good works', 'Good Works in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of good works as a vital aspect of a believer''s life. Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining good works and the positive impact they have on others.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 14, 2, 16, 16, 'Joppa', 'Connection through Joppa', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Joppa, linking the activities of Tabitha, known for her good works, with the logistical efforts involving wood transport to Jerusalem. This connection highlights the significance of Joppa as a place of service and community.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 44, 10, 31, 31, 'good works and almsdeeds which she did', 'Connection of Good Works and Alms', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of good works and almsgiving. Tabitha is noted for her ''good works and almsdeeds,'' while Cornelius''s ''alms'' are remembered by God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 58, 13, 21, 21, 'full of good works', 'Connection of Good Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of good works in both passages. Tabitha is described as ''full of good works,'' while Hebrews encourages believers to be ''perfect in every good work.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 15, 3, 7, 7, 'good works and almsdeeds which she did', 'Acts and Ezra''s Good Works', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of good works and charitable deeds. Tabitha is noted for her almsdeeds, while the people in Ezra are providing resources for rebuilding, reflecting a communal effort for good.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 36, 44, 10, 4, 5, 'good works and almsdeeds which she did', 'Connection of Almsgiving and Good Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of good deeds and almsgiving in both passages. Tabitha is noted for her ''good works and almsdeeds,'' while the angel acknowledges Cornelius''s ''prayers and thine alms'' as significant to God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 37, 44, 1, 13, 13, 'upper chamber', 'Connection of Upper Room References', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the ''upper room'' as a location for important events in the early church. In Acts 1:13, it serves as a gathering place for the apostles, while in Acts 9:37, it is where the deceased is laid, indicating a space of transition and community.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 37, 44, 20, 8, 8, 'upper chamber', 'Upper Chamber Significance', 'Both passages emphasize the ''upper chamber'' as a significant location. In Acts 9:37, it is where a deceased woman is laid, while in Acts 20:8, it serves as a gathering place for many.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 37, 41, 14, 15, 15, 'upper chamber', 'Upper Room Significance', 'Both passages emphasize the ''upper room'' as a significant location. In Acts, it serves as a place for mourning and preparation, while in Mark, it is a site for gathering and preparation for an important event.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 37, 43, 11, 3, 4, 'sick, and died', 'Connection of Death and Sickness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sickness leading to death. In Acts, the woman is sick and dies, while in John, the sickness is presented as not leading to death, highlighting a contrast in outcomes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 37, 43, 11, 36, 37, NULL, 'Connection of Death and Mourning', 'This connection highlights the theme of death and the response to it. Both passages reflect on the sorrow surrounding death, with Acts mentioning the washing and laying out of the deceased, while John emphasizes the grief expressed by those mourning Lazarus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 38, 44, 9, 36, 36, 'Joppa', 'Connection Between Joppa and Tabitha', 'Both passages emphasize Joppa as the location where significant events occur. The disciples in Lydda send for Peter to help Tabitha, highlighting her importance and the community''s response to her good works.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 38, 12, 4, 28, 30, 'desiring him that he would not delay', 'Urgency in Seeking Help', 'This connection highlights the urgency in both passages for seeking assistance in times of distress. In Acts, the disciples urgently send for Peter, while in 2 Kings, the mother insists on not leaving Elisha to help her child.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 38, 44, 9, 32, 32, NULL, 'Peter''s Journey to Lydda', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s movement to Lydda, highlighting his role among the saints. The mention of Peter in both contexts connects his ministry and the urgency of the disciples'' request.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 38, 44, 11, 26, 26, 'the disciples had heard that Peter was there', 'Connection of Disciples and Teaching', 'This connection highlights the role of disciples in spreading the teachings of Jesus. In both passages, the actions of the disciples lead to significant developments in the early church, culminating in the identification of believers as Christians.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 20, 10, 7, 7, NULL, 'Memory of the Just', 'This connection highlights the impact of Dorcas'' good deeds, as the widows weep and show her garments, reflecting the blessed memory of the just. Proverbs 10:7 emphasizes that the memory of the just is blessed, paralleling the remembrance of Dorcas'' kindness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 20, 31, 30, 31, 'the coats and garments which Dorcas made', 'Connection of Praising a Woman', 'Both passages emphasize the value of a woman''s works and character. In Acts, the widows show the garments made by Dorcas, while Proverbs praises a woman whose works are acknowledged.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 49, 4, 28, 28, NULL, 'Work and Generosity Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and generosity. In Acts, Dorcas is remembered for her good works and the garments she made, while Ephesians encourages working with one''s hands to provide for those in need.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 52, 1, 3, 3, 'coats and garments which Dorcas made', 'Work of Faith and Love', 'This connection highlights the theme of service and compassion in both passages. Dorcas''s acts of making garments for the widows reflect a ''work of faith'' and ''labour of love'' similar to what is commended in Thessalonians.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 10, 1, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Mourning and Clothing', 'This connection highlights the theme of mourning over individuals who provided for others through clothing. Both passages emphasize the significance of garments as a symbol of care and loss.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 18, 31, 19, 20, 'coats and garments which Dorcas made', 'Connection of Compassion and Clothing', 'This connection highlights the theme of caring for the needy through clothing. Both passages emphasize the importance of providing garments and support to those in need.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 39, 21, 9, 10, 10, 'coats and garments which Dorcas made', 'Work and Its Value', 'This connection highlights the importance of diligent work in life. In Acts, Dorcas is remembered for her good works, while Ecclesiastes emphasizes doing work with might before death. Both passages underscore the significance of meaningful contributions during one''s lifetime.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 40, 40, 9, 25, 25, 'arise', 'Resurrection Miracles by Peter and Jesus', 'This connection highlights the miraculous acts of resurrection performed by both Peter and Jesus. Both passages describe a scenario where individuals are raised from the dead after being addressed directly, emphasizing the power of their words.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 40, 41, 5, 40, 42, 'arise', 'Resurrection Commands in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize a command to arise, with Peter saying ''Tabitha, arise'' and Jesus saying ''Talitha cumi.'' This connection highlights the miraculous nature of resurrection in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 40, 42, 8, 54, 54, 'arise', 'Resurrection Commands', 'Both passages emphasize the command to arise from death. Peter and Jesus both perform miracles that restore life, showcasing their authority over death.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 9, 40, 12, 4, 32, 36, 'arise', 'Resurrection Miracles by Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the act of prayer preceding a miraculous resurrection. In each case, a prophet calls the deceased back to life, demonstrating a connection in the theme of divine intervention through prayer.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
